Definition 3.2. $($[4, Page 144]$)$ A subfunctor $F^{\prime}\subseteq F$ in $\mathbb{M}(\mathcal{M}^{op},\mathcal{G})$ is said to be pure subfunctor if the quotient functor $\dfrac{F}{F^{\prime}}\in\mathbb{M}(\mathcal{M}^{op},\mathcal{G})$. A mono functor is called absolutely pure if and only if whenever it appears as a subfunctor of a mono functor it is a pure subfunctor. We denote by $\mathcal{L}_{2}(\mathcal{M}^{op},\mathcal{G})\subseteq\mathbb{M}(\mathcal{M}^{% op},\mathcal{G})$ the full subcategory of absolutely pure functors [3].
Definition 2.4. $($[9, Definition 2.11]$)$ Let $\mathcal{M}$ be an additive category, $X:X^{0}\overset{d^{0}}{\rightarrow}X^{1}\overset{d^{1}}{\rightarrow}\cdots% \overset{d^{n-2}}{\rightarrow}X^{n-1}\overset{d^{n-1}}{\rightarrow}X^{n}$ a complex in $\mathcal{M}$ and $d^{0}:X^{0}\rightarrow Y^{0}$ a morphism in $\mathcal{M}$. An $n$-pushout diagram of $X$ along $d^{0}$ is a morphism of complexes $X$$X^{0}$$X^{1}$$\ldots$$X^{n-1}$$X^{n}$$Y$$Y^{0}$$Y^{1}$$\ldots$$Y^{n-1}$$Y^{n}$$f$$f^{0}$ such that in the mapping cone $C=C(f)$ is a right $n$-exact sequence. The concept of $n$-pullback diagram is defined dually.
Definition 2.1. ([9, Definition 2.4]) Let $\mathcal{M}$ be an additive category. A left $n$-exact sequence in $\mathcal{M}$ is a complex $X^{0}\overset{d^{0}}{\rightarrow}X^{1}\overset{d^{1}}{\rightarrow}\cdots% \overset{d^{n-1}}{\rightarrow}X^{n}\overset{d^{n}}{\rightarrow}X^{n+1}$ such that $(d^{0},\ldots,d^{n-1})$ is an $n$-kernel of $d^{n}$. The concept of right $n$-exact sequence is defined dually. An $n$-exact sequence is a sequence which is both a right $n$-exact sequence and a left $n$-exact sequence.
Definition 2.6. $($[9, Definition 3.14]$)$ Let $\mathcal{A}$ be an abelian category and $\mathcal{M}$ be a generating-cogenerating full subcategory of $\mathcal{A}$. $\mathcal{M}$ is called an $n$-cluster tilting subcategory of $\mathcal{A}$ if $\mathcal{M}$ is functorially finite in $\mathcal{A}$ and $\displaystyle\mathcal{M}$ $\displaystyle=\{X\in\mathcal{A}\mid\forall i\in\{1,\ldots,n-1\},\operatorname{% Ext}^{i}(X,\mathcal{M})=0\}$ $\displaystyle=\{X\in\mathcal{A}\mid\forall i\in\{1,\ldots,n-1\},\operatorname{% Ext}^{i}(\mathcal{M},X)=0\}.$ Note that $\mathcal{A}$ itself is the unique 1-cluster tilting subcategory of $\mathcal{A}$.
Definition 2.2. $($[9, Definition 3.1]$)$ An $n$-Abelian category is an additive category $\mathcal{M}$ which satisfies the following axioms: (A0) The category $\mathcal{M}$ is idempotent complete. (A1) Every morphism in $\mathcal{M}$ has an $n$-kernel and an $n$-cokernel. (A2) For every monomorphism $d^{0}:X^{0}\rightarrow X^{1}$ in $\mathcal{M}$ and for every $n$-cokernel $(d^{1},\ldots,d^{n})$ of $d^{0}$, the following sequence is $n$-exact: $X^{0}\overset{d^{0}}{\rightarrow}X^{1}\overset{d^{1}}{\rightarrow}\cdots% \overset{d^{n-1}}{\rightarrow}X^{n}\overset{d^{n}}{\rightarrow}X^{n+1}.$ (A3) For every epimorphism $d^{n}:X^{n}\rightarrow X^{n+1}$ in $\mathcal{M}$ and for every $n$-kernel $(d^{0},\ldots,d^{n-1})$ of $d^{n}$, the following sequence is $n$-exact: $X^{0}\overset{d^{0}}{\rightarrow}X^{1}\overset{d^{1}}{\rightarrow}\cdots% \overset{d^{n-1}}{\rightarrow}X^{n}\overset{d^{n}}{\rightarrow}X^{n+1}.$
Definition 1.2. [OT, Definition 5.3] Let $\mathcal{C}$ be an $(n+2)$-angulated category with an $n$-suspension functor $\Sigma^{n}$. An object $T\in\mathcal{C}$ is called cluster tilting if (1) $\mbox{Hom}_{\mathcal{C}}(T,\Sigma^{n}T)=0$. (2) For any object $C\in\mathcal{C}$, there exists an $(n+2)$-angle $T_{0}\xrightarrow{~{}~{}}T_{1}\xrightarrow{~{}~{}}\cdots\xrightarrow{~{}~{}}T_% {n-1}\xrightarrow{~{}~{}}T_{n}\xrightarrow{~{}~{}}C\xrightarrow{~{}~{}}\Sigma^% {n}T_{0}$ where $T_{0},T_{1},\cdots,T_{n}\in\mathsf{add}\hskip 0.7227ptT$.
Definition 1.3. [JJ2, Definitions 0.2 and 0.3] Let $\mathcal{C}$ be an $(n+2)$-angulated category with an $n$-suspension functor $\Sigma^{n}$. (1) An object $T\in\mathcal{C}$ is called $n$-rigid if ${\rm Hom}_{\mathcal{C}}(T,\Sigma^{n}T)=0$. (2) An object $T\in\mathcal{C}$ is called maximal $n$-rigid if it is rigid and maximal with respect to the property: $\mathsf{add}\hskip 0.7227ptT=\{M\in\mathcal{C}\ |\ {\rm Hom}_{\mathcal{C}}(T% \oplus M,\Sigma^{n}(T\oplus M))=0\}.$ (3) An object $T\in\mathcal{C}$ is called $n$-self-perpendicular object if $\mathsf{add}\hskip 0.7227ptT=\{M\in\mathcal{C}\ |\ {\rm Hom}_{\mathcal{C}}(T,% \Sigma^{n}M)=0\}=\{M\in\mathcal{C}\ |\ {\rm Hom}_{\mathcal{C}}(M,\Sigma^{n}T)=% 0\}.$
